# Error Catalog - Consistency and Coverage

## Purpose
- Standardize error shapes and types across apps.
- Make errors predictable for clients and observable for ops.

## Base Pattern
- All app-specific errors inherit from `apps.core.exceptions.BaseAPIException`.
- Each app defines its own hierarchy in `apps/{app_name}/helpers/exceptions.py`.
- Never raise raw `Exception` for domain errors—use typed exceptions.

## Structure of Errors
- HTTP status code appropriate to the condition (4xx client, 5xx server).
- Fields:
  - `message`: human-readable summary
  - `type`: exception class name
  - `details`: dict with structured context (IDs, constraints, limits)
- Do **not** include secrets or PII in `details`.

## Common Error Types (suggested)
- `ValidationError` (422) – input/contract violations
- `NotFoundError` (404) – missing resource
- `ConflictError` (409) – uniqueness/state conflicts (incl. idempotency conflicts)
- `UnauthorizedError` (401) – auth missing/invalid
- `ForbiddenError` (403) – insufficient permissions
- `RateLimitError` (429) – too many requests (usually middleware)
- `ServiceUnavailableError` (503) – dependencies unavailable

## Domain-Specific Errors
- Add per-domain subclasses (e.g., `OrderNotFoundError`, `PaymentFailedError`).
- Keep names specific and consistent; reuse core base classes.
- Include stable identifiers in `details` (e.g., `order_id`, `user_id`).

## Contract and Versioning
- Changing error types/status codes is a breaking change—version or deprecate.
- Add new error types additively; do not repurpose existing ones.

## Observability
- Log errors with context (no secrets/PII).
- Metrics: track error counts by type/status (low-cardinality labels).
